Ground rules
10 design principles for VR
5 x Basics & 5 x Immersion

Base rule 1: CURSOR
- Accessible, easy to implement and understand
- Unobtrusive... but not too much
- Later also possible to combine with Fuse

Base rule 2: Interface depth
-In 3D, there's more to consider than just pixels
-Take distnace, contrast, and lighting into account

Base rile 3: Constant speed
- Avoid varying speeds in motion
- Constant speed is desired
- You don't wat a rollercoaster effect

Base rule 4: Ground the user
- Use a fixed point in VR world
- Make it clear what is 'stationary' and what is 'moving'

Base rule 5: Constant tracking
- Most important part
- There are various types of tracking, Degree of Freedom (DOF)
- Most simple VR headset hace 3DOF
- ^DOF is possible with (external) head tracking

Immersion 1: Lighting
- Users look at the brightest point
- Just like with traditional design
- Subtle way to draw attention
- Can be done easily in A-Frame

Immersion 2: Usage of scale
- Large object really appear BIG
- Use the advantage compared to 3D

Immersion 3: Spatial audio
- Adds an extra layer of experience to 3D
- Works well in A-Frame
- Preferably with headphones

Immersion 4: Sightlines
- You always know where is your user is looking, take advantage of that
- Sometimes the user doesn't look where you want

Immersion 5: Make it beautiful
- It remains an illusion; you dont't want to break it
- Pay attention to details; this makes a concept more beautiful
- Keep your style consistent. Don't mix hyper-real with cartoon